Node.js persistent setup pattern:
1) Install/ensure `jazz-napi` is present; create one singleton context in a server-only module.
```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data" },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
});
```
- Runtime/lifetime: create once at startup, reuse for all requests, and call `await jazz.shutdown()` on process exit (SIGINT/SIGTERM) in long-running servers.
- Driver constraints: persistent driver (`type: "persistent"`) gives durable local runtime state; if you switch to memory driver, `serverUrl` is required because memory is ephemeral.
- Secrets: `BACKEND_SECRET` required for `asBackend()/forRequest()/forSession()/withAttribution*` server scopes; `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` is for schema/catalog/migration/admin operations only. Keep both server-only (not exposed in public env or client bundles).

Use `null` for optional refs. `undefined` means no change.

```ts
await db.update(app.todos, todoId, {
  projectId: null,
});
```
If you need to clear many optional fields, set each to `null` explicitly.

Pass a query accessor (not a prebuilt query) when inputs are reactive.

```ts
// Svelte
const todosSub = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  app.todos.where({ done: onlyOpen() }).orderBy("title", "asc")
);
// read: todosSub.current | todosSub.loading | todosSub.error
```

```tsx
// Solid
const [onlyOpen, setOnlyOpen] = createSignal(true);
const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: app.todos.where({ done: onlyOpen() }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
}));
```

If query inputs are static, pass a built query directly (no accessor).

Use `db.batch(...)` for optimistic UI-only grouping where local visibility is enough and no strict server-atomicity is required. Use `db.transaction(...)` when both writes must be authority-validated and become globally visible together.

```ts
// Optimistic UI group
const b = db.batch((tx) => {
  tx.insert(app.todos, { title: "A", done: false });
  tx.update(app.todos, todoBId, { done: true });
});
await b.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

```ts
// Authority-gated atomic group
const t = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, todoAId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, todoBId, { done: true });
});
await t.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Use a projection+decoder boundary for every query/write path.

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct TodoRow { id: ObjectId, title: String, done: bool, description: Option<String> }

fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, v: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    if v.len() != 4 { return Err(AppError::Decode("wrong projection length".into())); }
    let title = match &v[0] { Value::Text(t) => t.clone(), _ => return Err(AppError::Decode(...)) };
    let done = match &v[1] { Value::Boolean(b) => *b, _ => return Err(AppError::Decode(...)) };
    let description = match &v[2] { Value::Null => None, Value::Text(t) => Some(t.clone()), _ => return Err(AppError::Decode(...)) };
    Ok(TodoRow { id, title, done, description })
}
```

- Build schema once with `SchemaBuilder`/`TableSchema::builder`.
- Use `QueryBuilder` with explicit columns and one stable projection order.
- Map `Vec<(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)>` to `TodoRow` in one helper and reuse it everywhere.
- Writes: use `row_input!` for inserts, `update(...)` for mutations, and `client.wait_for_batch(batch, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer | GlobalServer)` before returning if required.
- Reject nullability/variant mismatches centrally; never do ad-hoc positional decoding in handlers.

```rust
let q = QueryBuilder::select("todos").column("title").column("done").column("description");
let rows = db.query(q).await?;
let typed: Result<Vec<_>, _> = rows.into_iter().map(|(id, v)| decode_todo(id,v)).collect();
```

Use one trusted client in app state and scope to caller per request.

```rust
async fn update_todo(
    State(app): State<AppState>,
    session: Session, // from verified caller auth/session extractor
    Path(id): Path<String>,
    Json(req): Json<UpdateTodoReq>,
) -> Result<Json<TodoRow>, ApiError> {
    let db = app.jazz_client.for_session(session);
    let batch = db.update(ObjectId::from_str(&id)?, vec![("done".into(), Value::Boolean(req.done))])?;
    tokio::time::timeout(Duration::from_secs(3), db.wait_for_batch(batch, DurabilityTier::GlobalServer)).await
        .map_err(|_| ApiError::GatewayTimeout)??;

    let row = db.query(QueryBuilder::select("todos").row(ObjectId::from_str(&id)?).column("title").column("done").column("description")).await?;
    let (id, vals) = row.into_iter().next().ok_or(ApiError::NotFound)?;
    Ok(Json(decode_todo(id, &vals)?))
}
```

- Authenticate bearer/session token first, then map to a stable Jazz `Session`.
- Never use backend/admin credential as caller identity for reads/writes.
- Use `db = client.for_session(session)` for both reads and writes so policy/authorship aligns.
- Return authority-visible results only after bounded batch wait.
- Error map: unauth→401, bad input→400/422, missing/filtered row→404, policy reject→403, timeout/disconnect→503/504, decode mismatch→500-safe message.

Use real topology with server + independent participants; avoid route re-implementation.

- Start test JWT issuer + `JazzServer` with schema/permissions.
- Create trusted service client (backend credential) and three participants: `alice`, `bob`, `charlie` (independent `JazzClient`s).
- Exercise the production router/factory through ephemeral listener or `tower::Service`.

```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn todo_update_scoped_by_caller_and_visible_cross_client() {
  // setup issuer, server, app clients, and routes
  // seed row as alice (wait_for_batch(EdgeServer))
  // call PUT/POST as bob via real HTTP route
  // query row via a separate client and decode with decode_todo
  // assert creator==alice, updater==bob, row is present and fields changed
  // call same route as charlie (denied user) and assert 403/404
}
```

- Prefer `JazzClient::test_client` only if one-runtime behavior is sufficient; otherwise use the external server path for permissions/transport/durability.
- Use `wait_for_query` / bounded retries for deterministic read-after-write assertions.
- If permission simulation requires it, use `connect_with_row_policy_mode(..., RowPolicyMode::PermissiveLocal)` only where necessary.
- Assert shutdown/cleanup: stop listener, issuer, server, and all clients/subsystems at end.

Use `counter` for the integer field and `g-set` for tags, both with non-null defaults.

```ts
const schema = {
  stats: s.table({
    score: s.int().default(0), // non-nullable
  }),
  docs: s.table({
    tags: s.array(s.string()).default([]),
  }),
};
```

Then:
1. `score: s.int().default(0).merge("counter")`
2. `tags: s.array(s.string()).default([]).merge("g-set")`

Rules:
- `counter` only for non-null integer snapshots; concurrent values are merged by ancestor delta summation, e.g., base 10, concurrent writes to 12 and 9 -> 11.
- `g-set` only for non-null array; concurrent additions converge to deduplicated union with ancestor elements.
- For this model, if you need removals, provenance, exact-once intent, or auditability, model as append-only operation rows instead of relying on merge.
- If you later change merge strategy in an existing schema, test old/new clients together (consumer-schema-relative resolution).

Use a real local server topology and assert convergence via normalized row sets (not implicit order).

```ts
import { afterEach, beforeEach, expect, it, vi } from "vitest";
import { createDb } from "jazz-tools";
import { deploy, startLocalJazzServer } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { app } from "../schema";
import permissions from "../permissions";

it("syncs multiple rows across clients with deterministic assertions", async () => {
  const server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  await deploy({
    serverUrl: server.url,
    appId: server.appId,
    adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
    schema: app,
    permissions,
  });

  const alice = await createDb({
    appId: server.appId,
    serverUrl: server.url,
    adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
    driver: { type: "memory" },
  });
  const bob = await createDb({
    appId: server.appId,
    serverUrl: server.url,
    adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
    driver: { type: "memory" },
  });

  // local-first visibility can be asserted on Alice immediately if needed
  const a = await alice.insert(app.items, { title: "A" }).wait({ tier: "edge" });
  const b = await alice.insert(app.items, { title: "B" }).wait({ tier: "edge" });
  const c = await alice.insert(app.items, { title: "C" }).wait({ tier: "edge" });

  const expected = [
    { id: a.id, title: a.title },
    { id: b.id, title: b.title },
    { id: c.id, title: c.title },
  ].sort((x, y) => x.title.localeCompare(y.title));

  await vi.waitFor(async () => {
    const rows = await bob.all(app.items, { tier: "edge" });
    const observed = rows
      .map((r) => ({ id: r.id, title: r.title }))
      .sort((x, y) => x.title.localeCompare(y.title));

    expect(observed).toEqual(expected);
  });

  await alice.shutdown();
  await bob.shutdown();
  await server.stop();
});
```

Use `.sort(...)` (or explicit stable key projection) for every multi-row comparison so the test is not order-sensitive.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` and assert both denied read and denied write with separate sessions.

```ts
import { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
import { createPolicyTestApp, type PolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { app } from "../schema";
import permissions from "../permissions";

let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

describe("Alice row isolation", () => {
  it("denies Bob from reading and updating Alice's row", async () => {
    const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
    const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });

    const aliceRow = alice.insert(app.notes, { body: "private" }).value;

    // Read-policy check: denied reads appear as filtered rows
    await expect(bob.all(app.notes.where({ id: aliceRow.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);

    // Write-policy check
    bob.expectDenied((db) => db.update(app.notes, aliceRow.id, { body: "tamper" }));

    // Optional control: owner remains able to update
    alice.expectAllowed((db) => db.update(app.notes, aliceRow.id, { body: "updated by owner" }));
  });
});
```

If policy requires explicit ownership claims, include those in the `as(...)` sessions per your policy DSL (e.g., role/group fields).
